children.subject: When u p/nped EECS126 and cs189, how many other CS classes were you taking? just curious
the semester with 126, one other CS class; the semester with 189, 2 other CS classes
Anecdotally, I P/NP'd both EECS 126 and CS 189 and I am currently in the 5th year program, so in general P/NP'ing classes is probably not a huge deal.

history.content:
P/NP classes basically count as not taking them for the purposes of non-professional grad admissions. Not negative, but the class ends up being a complete waste of time. 

To be honest, if you want to go to grad school, your priorities are out of order. Dial way back on recruiting and focus more on school. Grad schools don't care at all about where you interned or what you did as a SWE.

Hi,


I'm currently taking 2 CS upper-divs, a double-major requirement, and EE16A this semester. I'm also pretty involved in my research lab and also recruited really hard since the beginning of the semester. All of these things have taken up a lot of time to the point where I've been falling behind in my classes, especially EE16A. I've been just going through the motions and I don't feel confident about circuits at all. 

I've already taken Math 54, so EE16A isn't a requirement for me really, I just took it to learn circuits before EE16B next semester. I'm confident I can pass EE16A. I want to P/NP EE16A so that I can focus on my other classes and just do really well in them, and not have to worry about EE16A. The only thing that concerns me is the effect it has on grad school. For reference my GPA is a ~3.8. I want to apply for the 5th year MS program, and I'm worried that a P in EE16A might look bad. Does anyone have any experience or thoughts they can share on this? Thanks!
history.subject: P/NP Effect on Grad School
